  1. Write a single function, tidydoc(), to take an argument of a downloaded book tibble and return it in tidy text format after doing the following.
  • Add line and chapter numbers as variables before removing any lines.
  • Unnest tokens at the word level.
  • Remove any Project Gutenberg formatting so only the words remain.
    • If you wind up with fewer words, look closely for the use of single right quote âââvs apostropheâââin Jungle.
    • They are different Unicode characters. You should add to the regex for str_extract().
    • To create a single right quote on a mac, use Shift+ Option + } to get â.
    • To create a single right quote on a windows keyboard use ALT + 8217. See Right Single Quotation Mark.
  • Remove any stop_words.
  • Filter out any NAs.
  • Remove any front matter (words before Chapter 1).
library(tidytext)

tidydoc <- function(book_tibble) {
  
 book_tibble |>
    mutate(
      linenumber = row_number(),
      chapter = cumsum(str_detect(text, regex(
        "^chapter [\\divxlc]|^_(?!Contents)(?!Note)[:alpha:]+-?[:alpha:]*_$", 
                                        ignore_case = TRUE)))) |>
    unnest_tokens(word, text) |>
    mutate(word = str_extract(word, "[a-zâ']+")) |>
    anti_join(stop_words, by = "word") |>
    filter(!is.na(word)) |>
    filter(chapter > 0) ->tidy_book
  
  return(tidy_book)
}

Explain the following regex example for finding chapter numbers.

  • c_pattern <- regex("(^chapter [\\divxlc]|^_(?!Contents)(?!Note)[:alpha:]+-?[:alpha:]*_$)", ignore_case = TRUE)

This regular expression matches lines starting with âchapterâ followed by Roman numerals, or chapter titles enclosed in underscores that do not contain âContentsâ or âNoteâ. The title may consist of one or more alphabetic characters, optionally followed by a hyphen and additional alphabetic characters. The expression also ignores case sensitivity.

In The Quest of the Silver Fleece, the emotions of trust and anticipation are the most prominent, while disgust and surprise are the least expressed.

In The Jungle, fear and trust are the most prominent emotions, while disgust and surprise are the least expressed.

When comparing the two books, The Jungle exhibits more dramatic emotional fluctuations, whereas The Quest of the Silver Fleece has relatively steadier emotions.

The drop in counts at the end of The Jungle is due to the final section containing much fewer than 500 lines, resulting in significantly lower sentiment counts for the last block.

The Quest of the Silver Fleece tells a story of love and struggle centered on African Americans. As a result, âloveâ is the most frequent positive word in the book. While positive words appear slightly more often than in the other book, negative words still outnumber positive ones overall.

The Jungle is a social critique novel that focuses on the struggles of the working class, exposing the poverty, exploitation, and corruption brought by industrialization. Consequently, negative words occur more frequently than positive ones, with the most common being âpoor,â âcold,â âlost,â and âhard,â all closely tied to themes of poverty.

From the chart, it can be observed that in the early part of The Quest of the Silver Fleece, the net sentiment in the Custom Bing version is more positive compared to the original version. This could be because the word âMissâ appears more frequently in the earlier part of the story, and after removing it from the negative sentiment words, the net sentiment in the early section becomes more positive.

On the other hand, in The Jungle, the Custom Bing version has fewer positive net sentiment values between the 50th and 70th segments compared to the original. This might be because the word âhotâ appears more frequently in this section, and after removing it from the positive sentiment words, the positive net sentiment in this segment decreases.
